WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Welcome everyone to AI-Assisted Software Development with GitHub Copilot.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:12.000
I'm John Miller and today we're going to explore how AI can transform your development workflow.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Let's start with an overview of what we'll cover in this afternoon session.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Section 1: Introduction to GitHub Copilot

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:35.000
GitHub Copilot is an AI-powered code completion tool that helps you write code faster.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:42.000
It uses advanced language models trained on billions of lines of code.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:50.000
The key benefit is that it understands context from your current file and can suggest entire functions.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:58.000
It supports dozens of programming languages and integrates directly into your IDE.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Let's look at some practical examples of how Copilot works in real development scenarios.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Section 2: Setting Up Your Development Environment

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:22.000
First, you need to install the GitHub Copilot extension in VS Code or your preferred IDE.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:30.000
You'll need an active GitHub Copilot subscription - either individual or through your organization.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:38.000
Once installed, sign in with your GitHub account to activate the extension.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:46.000
Let me show you the configuration options that are most important for productivity.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:55.000
You can customize suggestion behavior, enable or disable inline suggestions, and set up keyboard shortcuts.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:03.000
I recommend keeping the default settings initially until you understand your preferences.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:12.000
Section 3: Basic Copilot Features

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:20.000
Subsection 3.1: Inline Code Completion

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:28.000
As you type, Copilot suggests completions in gray text - press Tab to accept.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:36.000
You can cycle through alternative suggestions using Alt+] or Alt+[.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:44.000
Copilot learns from your coding patterns and improves suggestions over time.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:52.000
For best results, write clear comments describing what you want to accomplish.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:02.000
Subsection 3.2: Chat Interface

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:10.000
The Copilot Chat panel lets you ask questions in natural language.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:18.000
You can request explanations of existing code or ask for implementation guidance.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:26.000
Chat understands context from your open files and workspace structure.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Use slash commands like /explain, /fix, or /tests for common operations.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:43.000
Section 4: Advanced Techniques

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:51.000
Now let's dive into more sophisticated ways to leverage Copilot's capabilities.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Subsection 4.1: Custom Agents and Promptfiles

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Custom agents allow you to create specialized AI assistants for specific tasks.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:15.000
They're defined in .agent.md files with YAML front matter and instructions.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Promptfiles are reusable task definitions that can be invoked with @ syntax.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Both features help you maintain consistency across your development workflow.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:40.000
Subsection 4.2: Context Management

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:48.000
Copilot's effectiveness depends heavily on the context you provide.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:56.000
Use #file references to include specific files in your chat context.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:04.000
Create instruction files in .github/instructions/ for project-wide guidance.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Good comments and clear naming help Copilot understand your intentions better.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Section 5: Best Practices and Common Pitfalls

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Let's discuss how to get the most value from Copilot while avoiding common mistakes.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:38.000
First, always review and test code generated by Copilot - never blindly accept suggestions.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Use descriptive variable names and function signatures to guide better completions.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:54.000
Break complex tasks into smaller, well-defined steps with clear comments.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:02.000
Be specific about requirements, especially for security-sensitive or business-critical code.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:10.000
Remember that Copilot is a tool to enhance productivity, not replace critical thinking.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:19.000
Section 6: Real-World Examples and Demos

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:27.000
